CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_dashboard'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Detect</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Dashboard</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Cross-product detection overview — cases, detections timeline, MITRE ATT&CK heatmap, threat graphs, and geo-distribution</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Threat Analysis Center Dashboard is the operational security command centre in Sophos Central. It surfaces a live count of open cases by status, a detection timeline bar chart showing volume across the selected time period, a MITRE ATT&CK heatmap highlighting which tactics and techniques are being observed in the environment, a world map showing geographic distribution of detections, recent threat graphs, top 10 affected entities and users, and a list of recently run Live Discover queries. All widgets are interactive — clicking into any element drills down to the underlying data. The time range defaults to the last 24 hours and can be adjusted to 1 hour, 7 days, or 30 days.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"This is where XDR and MDR investigations start. Everything you\'re seeing here is live, drawn from data that your endpoints, servers, firewalls, and third-party tools are uploading to the Sophos Data Lake in real time. The cases widget at the top shows open investigations by status — action required, in progress, resolved. The detections timeline below shows the volume and severity of suspicious activity detected across the estate over the selected period. But the two things I always highlight first are the MITRE ATT&CK heatmap and the geographic detection map. The heatmap shows you which attack tactics are actively being observed in your environment right now — not theoretically, based on your specific telemetry. If you hover over a tactic you see the breakdown by technique. If you click it you see the specific detections behind it. For a CISO presenting to a board, that heatmap answers the question: which stages of the attack kill chain are we actually seeing in our environment today?\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Live detection timeline</strong> — bar chart of detections by severity over the selected period; spikes indicate bursts of suspicious activity worth investigating</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>MITRE ATT&CK heatmap</strong> — shows which tactics and techniques are actively observed in the environment; click any tactic to drill into the specific detections behind it</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Cases widget</strong> — open investigation count by status; Action Required cases need immediate attention; Sophos-managed means MDR analysts are already working it</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Geographic detection map</strong> — world map showing where detections are originating; useful for identifying unexpected geographic anomalies such as logins from unusual locations</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Top 10 entities and users</strong> — identifies the most frequently appearing devices and accounts in detections; chronic repeat appearances indicate persistent risk worth investigating</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Open the Threat Analysis Center Dashboard. Start with the cases widget — show the status breakdown and explain what Action Required means. Move to the detections timeline and adjust the time range to show a 7-day view. Click the MITRE ATT&CK heatmap and hover over the most active tactic — show the technique breakdown. Click through to the underlying detections list. Return to the Dashboard and show the Top 10 entities — click the highest appearing device to show the investigation path. Ask the customer which of these signals they currently have visibility of in their existing tooling.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_cases'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Detect</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Cases</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Correlated investigation workspace — auto-grouped detections, MITRE mapping, analyst notes, and AI-assisted case summaries</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Cases page groups related detections into structured investigations. Cases are created automatically when Sophos identifies related detections that belong to the same attack sequence, or manually by security analysts. Each case shows its managed-by status — Sophos-managed cases are handled by the MDR analyst team, Self-managed cases require the customer\'s own analyst to investigate and respond. Case details include the full list of correlated detections, MITRE ATT&CK tactics and techniques observed, a Notebook tab for analyst investigation notes, recent activity history, and for XDR customers an AI-generated case summary and AI-assisted command line analysis. The status workflow moves from Action Required through Investigating to Resolved.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Cases are where the power of XDR correlation becomes visible. Instead of an analyst triaging hundreds of individual detections — a process that generates alert fatigue and causes critical signals to be missed — the Cases engine automatically groups related detections from across your estate into a single structured investigation. A process on an endpoint that spawned a suspicious child process, made an outbound connection to an unusual destination, and then wrote a file to a sensitive location — those three separate detections become one Case with a clear attack narrative. For MDR customers you\'ll see these cases marked as Sophos-managed, which means our analyst team has already picked this up, is actively investigating, and will reach out if they need your input or if they\'ve already taken containment action. For XDR customers without MDR, each Self-managed case has an assigned admin who owns the investigation. The AI case summary gives them an immediate plain-language explanation of what happened — no SQL, no query language, just an analyst-quality write-up generated in seconds.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Auto-correlation</strong> — related detections from across endpoint, server, network, email, and identity are grouped automatically into one case rather than appearing as separate unconnected alerts</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Sophos-managed vs Self-managed</strong> — MDR customers see Sophos-managed cases where analysts are actively working the investigation; XDR customers own and work Self-managed cases themselves</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>AI case summary</strong> — XDR customers can generate an AI-written plain-language summary of the case in seconds; no SQL or query expertise required to understand what happened</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>MITRE ATT&CK mapping per case</strong> — every case shows which tactics and techniques were involved; click through to the MITRE website for technique detail and adversary playbook context</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Notebook tab</strong> — analysts document their investigation steps, findings, and actions in the case Notebook; creates an auditable investigation record for compliance and post-incident review</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Cases. Filter to show Action Required cases first. Click into a case and walk through the structure — show the correlated detections list, the MITRE tactics observed, and the AI case summary for XDR customers. Show the Notebook tab and explain the investigation documentation workflow. For MDR customers highlight the Sophos-managed label and explain that analyst action is already underway. Show how the status changes from Action Required through Investigating to Resolved.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_detections'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Detect</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Detections</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Suspicious activity signals from the Sophos Data Lake — severity-ranked, MITRE-mapped, with enrichment and response actions</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Detections page shows all suspicious activity identified across the estate, drawn from data uploaded to the Sophos Data Lake by endpoints, servers, and integrated third-party tools. Detections are displayed as a bar chart timeline and a ranked list. Each detection includes its severity level, the source device and user, the MITRE ATT&CK tactic and technique, threat intelligence enrichments linking to SophosLabs Intelix and VirusTotal, and direct response actions including device scan, isolation, and Live Response terminal access. Detections that share characteristics are automatically grouped into Cases. The default view covers the last 24 hours and can be filtered by entity, severity, threat type, and operating system.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Detections are the raw signal layer — everything that the Sophos XDR engine has flagged as suspicious across your estate, ranked by severity and mapped to the MITRE ATT&CK framework. The important distinction to make here is that these are not alerts in the traditional sense. Traditional security tools generate alerts on known signatures. XDR detections are based on behavioural analysis of data uploaded to the Sophos Data Lake — they identify unusual patterns and anomalies that indicate potential compromise, even when no known malware signature is present. Click into any detection and you see exactly what the system observed, which device and user was involved, which MITRE tactic and technique it maps to, and what actions are available. From a single detection detail pane you can launch a Live Response terminal to the affected device, run a targeted Live Discover query to hunt for the same indicator across the rest of the estate, or initiate device isolation — all without leaving this screen.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Behavioural detection not just signatures</strong> — XDR detections identify anomalous patterns and suspicious behaviours in Data Lake telemetry that signature-based tools miss</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>MITRE ATT&CK mapping</strong> — every detection is tagged with the tactic and technique it represents; click through to MITRE for adversary playbook context and recommended defensive action</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Threat intelligence enrichments</strong> — SophosLabs Intelix and VirusTotal links built into each detection; one click to external reputation and analysis without leaving the console</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Inline response actions</strong> — scan, isolate, and Live Response all accessible from the detection detail pane; no separate workflow or tool-switching required</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Automatic case grouping</strong> — related detections are automatically grouped into Cases; the Cases column in each detection shows which investigation it belongs to</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Detections. Filter to Critical severity to show the highest priority items. Click into a detection and walk through the full detail pane — show the device and user, the MITRE tactic, and the enrichment links. Demonstrate the response action options — show where device isolation and Live Response are accessible. Show how to escalate a detection to a Case manually. Change the time range to 7 days to show the detection volume trend.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_device_exposure'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Detect</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Device Exposure</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Windows devices with extended OS update gaps — identifies patch exposure risk for XDR and MDR customers</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Device Exposure helps XDR and MDR customers identify Windows devices that have not installed an operating system update for an extended period. The page surfaces devices with the greatest patch gap — showing the device name, operating system version, last seen date, and how long since the last OS update was applied. Unpatched Windows devices represent a significant attack surface since many high-profile exploits specifically target known OS vulnerabilities that patches address. Device Exposure provides the visibility needed to prioritise patch remediation efforts based on actual exposure duration rather than relying on vulnerability scanner outputs alone.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Device Exposure answers a simple but critical question: which of your Windows devices are most exposed right now because they haven\'t been patched? Unpatched operating systems are one of the most consistent factors in successful breaches. Attackers specifically target known CVEs in Windows because they know patching is never 100 percent complete across any real-world estate. What this page does is surface the devices with the longest patch gap — the ones that have gone the longest without an OS update — so your team can prioritise remediation based on actual exposure duration. This is particularly valuable for identifying devices that were offline for extended periods and came back onto the network without going through the update cycle, or devices in operational technology environments where maintenance windows are infrequent. Combined with the Detections page, if a device appearing here is also generating detections, that combination of patch exposure plus suspicious activity is a priority escalation signal.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Patch gap visibility</strong> — shows which Windows devices have gone the longest without an OS update; surfaces the exposure that attackers actively exploit</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Priority-based remediation</strong> — rank devices by update gap duration to focus patching effort on the highest-risk devices first rather than working through a flat list</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Offline device risk</strong> — devices that were offline and returned without patching are a common blind spot; Device Exposure surfaces them immediately</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Cross-signal correlation</strong> — if a device in Device Exposure is also generating detections it represents a compounded risk — patch exposure plus active suspicious activity</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Device Exposure under Threat Analysis Center. Show the list sorted by longest update gap. Click a device to show its detail — OS version, last seen, and update status. Correlate with the Detections page by searching for the same device name. Position this as the bridge between patch management and threat detection — the devices most likely to be successfully exploited are the ones that are both unpatched and generating suspicious signals.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_ai_search'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Investigate</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">AI Search</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Natural language Data Lake search — query detections and endpoint data without writing SQL</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">AI Search allows analysts to query the Sophos Data Lake using natural language questions rather than SQL. It searches two data types: Detections — the threat detection records across the estate — and Endpoint Data — activity data from Windows devices including processes, files, network connections, registry changes, and authentications. Analysts type a plain-language question such as \"show me PowerShell processes that made outbound connections in the last 24 hours\" and AI Search builds and runs the appropriate Data Lake query, returning results in a structured table. Results are capped at 1000 rows and retained for 90 days by default, or up to 1 year with the Data 1-Year Storage Pack licence. Queries can be saved and reused in Live Discover for scheduled or repeated hunting.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"AI Search is the capability that makes XDR accessible to analysts who are not Data Lake query experts. Historically, getting meaningful answers out of a security data lake required an analyst to know the schema, understand the query language, and write correct SQL — a skill set that not every SOC has available. AI Search removes that barrier entirely. An analyst types a question in plain English — something like: which users authenticated to this server between midnight and 6am last Thursday — and the system builds and runs the query for them. The results come back in a table they can act on immediately. This is particularly powerful for smaller teams or organisations building out their XDR capability where dedicated threat hunting expertise is limited. It is also a significant time saver for experienced analysts who want fast answers without context-switching into a query editor. Queries saved here can be promoted into Live Discover for scheduled ongoing hunting.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>No SQL required</strong> — natural language questions are converted to Data Lake queries automatically; any analyst can investigate without query language expertise</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Two search domains</strong> — Detections searches threat detection records; Endpoint Data searches Windows device activity including processes, files, network connections, and authentications</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>IOC hunting</strong> — search for specific indicators of compromise including IP addresses, file hashes, domain names, and usernames across the full data retention window</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Save and promote to Live Discover</strong> — effective queries can be saved and run as scheduled Live Discover queries for ongoing proactive hunting without manual re-entry</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Requires EDR, XDR, or MDR licence</strong> — AI Search is available to customers with Sophos EDR, XDR, or MDR; Data Lake retention is 90 days standard or 1 year with the Storage Pack add-on</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to AI Search under Investigate. Select Detections as the data type. Type a natural language question such as \"show me critical severity detections in the last 7 days involving PowerShell\" and run the search. Show the results table and walk through the columns. Save the query. Switch to Endpoint Data and run a search for a specific process name or IP address to demonstrate the endpoint activity hunting capability. Show where the saved query appears in Live Discover for scheduled use.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_threat_graphs'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Investigate</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Threat Graphs</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Visual attack chain diagrams — root cause, lateral movement, process trees, and suggested remediation steps</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Threat Graphs are automatically generated visual diagrams showing how a detected threat entered the environment, how it progressed, and which processes, files, registry keys, and users were involved. Each graph is generated when Sophos detects malware or suspicious activity that requires deeper investigation. The graph detail page shows a Summary with root cause, affected files, device and user details, and detection timestamp; Suggested next steps including priority level, status, and remediation guidance; a visual diagram of the attack chain showing parent-child process relationships; a list of affected artifacts; and for XDR customers the ability to isolate the device directly from the graph detail view. Graphs can also be generated manually from Live Discover query results.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Threat Graphs are how Sophos answers the question that every security team asks after a detection: how did this happen and how far did it go? When our deep learning or behavioural engine detects something on an endpoint, we automatically reconstruct the full attack chain from the telemetry we have — working backwards from the detection to find the root cause, and forwards to show every process it spawned, every file it touched, every registry key it modified. What you\'re seeing on screen is not a static report — it\'s a live reconstruction of the attack as it happened on that specific device. The root cause tells you the initial access vector. The process tree shows you exactly what the malware did step by step. The suggested next steps panel gives you a prioritised remediation workflow. And if you\'re running XDR, you can isolate the device directly from this screen in a single click — cutting off the attacker\'s access without any additional tooling.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Root cause analysis</strong> — every threat graph shows where the attack entered the environment; eliminates the manual forensic work of tracing the infection source</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Visual attack chain</strong> — parent-child process tree shows exactly what the malware did step by step; immediate context for scoping the impact without manual log analysis</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Artifact inventory</strong> — files, registry keys, and network connections involved in the attack are listed with the graph; complete scope of what needs remediation</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Suggested next steps</strong> — automated priority assignment and remediation guidance built into every graph; no prior threat intelligence expertise required to take the right action</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>One-click device isolation (XDR)</strong> — isolate the affected device directly from the threat graph without switching to a separate tool or workflow</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Threat Graphs under Investigate. Open a recent graph and start with the Summary section — show the root cause and the initial access vector. Walk through the process tree visual and explain what parent-child relationships indicate. Show the suggested next steps and explain how priority is assigned. Show the Artifacts list. For XDR customers demonstrate where the device isolation option appears. Optionally show how to generate a manual threat graph from a Live Discover query result.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_live_discover'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Investigate</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Live Discover</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Real-time and Data Lake query platform — hunt for threats, check compliance, and investigate device activity across the estate</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Live Discover provides a structured query platform for investigating devices and Data Lake telemetry. It supports two query modes: Endpoint Queries which run in real time against online managed devices, and Data Lake Queries which run against the historical telemetry uploaded by devices to the Sophos Data Lake. Live Discover includes a library of pre-built queries organised into categories covering threat hunting, compliance checking, process investigation, file analysis, authentication events, and network activity. Custom queries can be created in Designer Mode. Queries can be scheduled for recurring execution. Live Discover requires Sophos EDR, XDR, or MDR. It is the primary hands-on investigation and threat hunting tool in Sophos Central.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Live Discover is the investigation workbench for analysts who want to go beyond what the automated detection surface tells them. There are two fundamentally different things you can do here. Endpoint queries run in real time against your online managed devices — you ask a question and within seconds you get an answer drawn directly from the current state of that device. Is this process running? Is this file present? Has anyone authenticated in the last hour? You\'re getting live answers, not historical snapshots. Data Lake queries are different — they search across the telemetry that all your devices have been continuously uploading to the Sophos Data Lake. That gives you historical depth. You can ask: across my entire estate, over the last 30 days, which devices ran PowerShell with encoded arguments? The pre-built query library means your analysts can start hunting immediately without writing a single line of SQL — but Designer Mode is there for analysts who want to build custom queries for their specific environment. For organisations that have had a security incident and want to answer: did this IOC appear anywhere else in our estate before we caught it — Live Discover is where that answer lives.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Two query modes</strong> — Endpoint Queries get live real-time answers from online devices; Data Lake Queries search historical telemetry across the full retention window</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Pre-built query library</strong> — organised by category covering threat hunting, compliance, process investigation, file analysis, authentications, and network activity; ready to run without writing SQL</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Designer Mode</strong> — experienced analysts can write custom SQL queries for environment-specific investigation scenarios beyond the pre-built library</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Scheduled queries</strong> — queries can be scheduled for recurring automatic execution; supports proactive ongoing threat hunting without manual re-running</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">5</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Requires EDR, XDR, or MDR</strong> — Live Discover is the core hands-on investigation capability for all Sophos XDR and MDR customers</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Live Discover under Investigate. Show the pre-built query library categories — highlight Threat Hunting, Process Queries, and Authentication Events. Select a pre-built endpoint query such as Recently Run Processes, select a device, and run it live to show real-time results. Then switch to a Data Lake query — select a time range and run across the estate to show the historical scope. Show Designer Mode briefly. Demonstrate scheduling a query for recurring overnight execution. Explain the difference between endpoint and Data Lake query use cases.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_integrations'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Settings</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Integrations</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Third-party security tool connections — ingest telemetry from non-Sophos products into the XDR Data Lake</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Integrations section manages connections between Sophos Central and third-party security products — allowing telemetry from non-Sophos tools to be ingested into the Sophos Data Lake and made available for XDR detection, Live Discover querying, and Cases correlation. Integrations include endpoint products such as CrowdStrike and Microsoft Defender, firewall vendors, identity providers, cloud platforms, and SIEM systems. Connecting third-party tools extends XDR detection coverage beyond Sophos-managed devices to the full heterogeneous estate. MDR customers benefit from analyst investigation of third-party telemetry alongside Sophos-native signals.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"One of the most common objections we hear about XDR is: we already have CrowdStrike on our endpoints, we\'re not going to rip and replace. Integrations is the answer to that objection. Sophos XDR does not require you to replace existing security investments. You connect your existing tools here — CrowdStrike, Palo Alto, Microsoft Defender, Okta, whichever products are already in your environment — and their telemetry flows into the Sophos Data Lake alongside your Sophos-native data. From that point, every detection, every case, every Live Discover query runs across all of it simultaneously. You get cross-product correlation that no individual vendor can provide. And for MDR customers, our analysts investigate your CrowdStrike detections and your Sophos detections with the same depth — they\'re not limited to what the Sophos agent sees. The integrations library covers the most common enterprise security stack vendors and the connection process is typically completed in minutes.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Open XDR platform</strong> — Sophos XDR ingests telemetry from non-Sophos tools; customers keep existing security investments while gaining cross-product correlation</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Broad vendor coverage</strong> — integrations available for CrowdStrike, Microsoft Defender, Palo Alto, Okta, and many other common enterprise security stack tools</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>MDR cross-product investigation</strong> — MDR analyst team investigates third-party telemetry alongside Sophos-native signals; not limited to what Sophos agents see</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Data Lake unification</strong> — all integrated telemetry is normalised and available for Live Discover queries and Cases correlation across the full estate</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Integrations under Threat Analysis Center Settings. Show the available integrations library and highlight the breadth of vendor coverage. Walk through the connection process for a common integration such as Microsoft Defender or CrowdStrike. Show how integrated product data appears in the Detections page alongside Sophos-native detections. Position this as the answer to the rip-and-replace objection — existing security investments are extended not replaced.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_configured'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Settings</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Configured</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Active integration connections — manage, monitor, and update existing third-party data source connections</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Configured section shows all active integration connections that have been established between Sophos Central and third-party security tools. Each configured integration shows its connection status, the data types being ingested, the last successful data receipt timestamp, and management options for editing or removing the connection. This is the operational view of the integration estate — where administrators verify that connected tools are actively sending telemetry and troubleshoot connections that have stopped reporting.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Configured is the operational health check for your integration connections. Once you\'ve set up third-party integrations, this is where you confirm they\'re actively sending data. The most common issue we see is an integration that was set up correctly but silently stopped reporting — a credential rotation that wasn\'t updated, a network change that blocked the outbound connection, or an API key that expired. Configured shows you immediately which integrations are healthy and which have a status issue. For large environments with many connected tools, this is the first place to check when a customer reports that they\'re not seeing expected detections from a specific product.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Integration health at a glance</strong> — see which third-party connections are actively reporting data and which have connection issues</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Last data receipt timestamp</strong> — confirms that each integration is sending current telemetry; stale timestamps indicate a connection problem</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Credential and API key management</strong> — update authentication details for connected tools from this view without reconfiguring the full integration</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Configured under Settings. Show the list of active integrations with their status indicators. Click into an integration to show the detail — data types ingested, last receipt timestamp, and management options. Explain what a stale timestamp indicates and how to troubleshoot a failed integration connection. Position this as part of the ongoing operational maintenance workflow for XDR environments.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_marketplace'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Settings</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Marketplace</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Available integration library — browse and connect new third-party security tool integrations</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Marketplace is the catalogue of available third-party integrations that can be connected to Sophos Central XDR. It lists all supported vendor integrations organised by category — endpoint, network, identity, cloud, email, and SIEM. Each integration listing shows what data types are ingested, the licence requirements, and the steps to connect. The Marketplace is the starting point for expanding XDR coverage to new tools in the security stack.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Marketplace is where you browse what is available to connect. When a customer adds a new security tool to their environment — or when we\'re in a conversation where they mention they\'re running a specific product — this is where we show them whether that tool is already supported. The library is continuously expanding as Sophos adds new integration partners. For MDR customers the value of each new integration is multiplied because it extends the data our analysts can investigate — more connected tools means more complete visibility for the team watching your environment.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Browsable integration catalogue</strong> — organised by category; find available integrations for any component of the security stack</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Connection requirements</strong> — each listing shows licence requirements, supported data types, and the steps to establish the connection</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Continuously expanding</strong> — new integration partners are added regularly; the library grows as Sophos extends XDR coverage to additional vendor products</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Marketplace under Settings. Browse the available integrations by category — show endpoint, network, and identity categories. Click into a specific integration the customer is likely running — CrowdStrike or Palo Alto — and walk through what data types would be ingested. Show where to click to begin the connection process. Position Marketplace as the catalogue that answers the question: does Sophos XDR support the tools we already have?</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_detection_rules'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Settings</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Detection Rules</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Manage XDR detection rules — enable, disable, tune, and create custom detection logic for the environment</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Detection Rules manages the set of rules that drive XDR detections in Sophos Central. The page lists all active and inactive detection rules, showing each rule\'s name, category, severity level, MITRE ATT&CK mapping, and current status. Rules can be enabled or disabled individually. For organisations with specific known-good behaviours that trigger false positives, rules can be tuned using allow list conditions. XDR customers can also create custom detection rules for environment-specific scenarios not covered by the default rule set. The detection rule library is maintained and updated by Sophos X-Ops as new threat techniques emerge.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">\"Detection Rules gives you control over what the XDR engine is actively looking for in your environment. Out of the box, the default rule set is curated and maintained by Sophos X-Ops — our threat intelligence team — and updated continuously as new attack techniques are observed in the wild. But every environment has legitimate activities that look suspicious to an automated detection engine. A developer running encoded PowerShell commands for a build pipeline. An admin account accessing servers outside business hours for a scheduled maintenance task. Detection Rules is where you tune those known-good scenarios out of the detection surface without disabling the underlying rule entirely. And for organisations with specific threat hunting requirements — detecting a particular technique or pattern that the default rules don\'t cover — custom rule creation lets your team extend the detection library to match your specific threat model.\"</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">1</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>X-Ops maintained rule library</strong> — default detection rules are written and updated by Sophos X-Ops as new attack techniques emerge; no manual rule management required for baseline coverage</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">2</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Enable and disable by rule</strong> — turn specific rules on or off without affecting the rest of the detection surface; useful for managing rules that are not relevant to the environment</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">3</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Allow list tuning</strong> — suppress false positives for known-good behaviours without disabling the underlying detection logic; maintains detection coverage while reducing noise</p></div><div style=\"display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start\"><div style=\"background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px\">4</div><p style=\"margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6\"><strong>Custom rule creation</strong> — write environment-specific detection rules for scenarios not covered by the default library; extends XDR coverage to match the organisation\'s specific threat model</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Detection Rules under Settings. Show the full rule list with MITRE mapping and severity. Filter by a specific MITRE tactic to show rules covering that attack category. Click into a rule and show the allow list configuration — explain how to add a known-good exception without disabling the rule. Show the custom rule creation option and explain the use case. Explain how the rule library is maintained by Sophos X-Ops and automatically updated.</p></div></div>';
CENTRAL_CONTENT['tac_preferences'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Threat Analysis Center &rsaquo; Settings</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Preferences</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Threat Analysis Center configuration &mdash; Data Lake upload settings, data retention, notification preferences, and XDR behaviour configuration</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Preferences section controls the configuration settings that govern how the Threat Analysis Center operates &mdash; including Data Lake upload settings that control which device types and data categories upload telemetry, data retention period configuration, notification preferences for case status changes, and XDR behaviour settings such as automatic case creation thresholds. Preferences is typically configured during initial XDR deployment and revisited when expanding coverage to new device types or adjusting data retention to match compliance requirements.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Preferences is the configuration layer that determines what the Threat Analysis Center can see. The most important settings here during an XDR deployment are the Data Lake upload configurations &mdash; these control which of your device types are sending telemetry to the Data Lake and therefore which devices will appear in Detections, Cases, and Live Discover queries. If a device type is not configured to upload, it is invisible to XDR detection. During a deployment conversation, we always walk through Preferences to confirm that all relevant device types are configured to upload. The data retention setting is also worth noting in regulated environments &mdash; standard retention is 90 days but the 1-Year Storage Pack extends this for organisations that have compliance requirements around security telemetry retention.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Data Lake upload configuration</strong> &mdash; controls which device types and data categories send telemetry; devices not configured here are invisible to XDR detection and investigation</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Data retention settings</strong> &mdash; standard 90-day retention covers most investigation needs; the 1-Year Storage Pack extends retention for compliance requirements</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Deployment validation</strong> &mdash; Preferences is the first place to check if expected devices are not appearing in Detections or Live Discover; missing telemetry is almost always a Data Lake upload configuration issue</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Preferences under Settings. Show the Data Lake upload configuration and walk through which device types are currently enabled. Explain what happens if a device type is not configured. Show the data retention setting and explain the 90-day default versus the 1-Year Storage Pack. Show notification preferences for case status changes. Position Preferences as the deployment validation checklist &mdash; if expected data is missing, this is the first place to look.</p></div></div>';

