CENTRAL_CONTENT['reports_reports'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">Reports</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Reports</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Cross-product security reporting &mdash; endpoint, server, email, encryption, and threat intelligence reports with scheduling, export, and co-branded delivery</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Reports section in Sophos Central is the cross-product reporting library &mdash; a single location where administrators can generate, customise, schedule, and export security reports covering every Sophos product in the estate. Reports are organised by product area and include endpoint and server protection summaries, computer and server inventory reports, email security reports covering message activity, SophosLabs analysis verdicts, time-of-click URL protection, at-risk users, and post-delivery activity, threat reports including attack details and Intelix threat summaries, data control and compliance reports, and licence usage summaries. Every report supports date range filtering, category filtering, and search. Reports can be printed, exported to PDF or CSV, saved as named templates, and scheduled for automatic recurring delivery by email to any Sophos Central administrator. For MSP and partner administrators, reports automatically include co-branding with the partner and customer logos on PDF exports.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Every security platform generates data &mdash; the question is whether that data is getting out of the console and in front of the people who need to act on it. Reports in Sophos Central answers that. This is the single reporting library for your entire Sophos estate. Whatever product you are running &mdash; endpoint, server, email, encryption &mdash; the reports are all here in one place, not scattered across separate product portals. The two capabilities I always highlight in a demo are scheduling and co-branding. Scheduling means you configure a report once &mdash; pick your date range, your filters, your frequency &mdash; and it runs automatically and lands in the right inbox every week or every month without anyone having to remember to run it. That is how a CISO gets a monthly security posture report without chasing their IT team for it. For MSPs the co-branding capability is significant &mdash; every PDF report that goes to a customer automatically includes your partner logo and the customer logo. It becomes a branded deliverable that demonstrates value at renewal. The email security reports are worth spending time on in any deal where email is in scope &mdash; the Message Summary report gives you 365 days of inbound and outbound activity, the At Risk Users report identifies the specific mailboxes generating the most security events, and the Time of Click report shows whether URL rewriting is catching threats after delivery. Those three reports together tell the email security story in data.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Single reporting library</strong> &mdash; every Sophos product report in one place; no separate portals needed to compile a cross-product security posture summary</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Scheduled automated delivery</strong> &mdash; configure once and reports run automatically on a daily, weekly, or monthly cadence and are emailed directly to named administrators; eliminates manual report generation</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Co-branding for MSPs and partners</strong> &mdash; PDF reports automatically include partner and customer logos; turns a raw security export into a branded deliverable at renewal</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Email security reports depth</strong> &mdash; Message Summary covers up to 365 days of activity; At Risk Users identifies highest-risk mailboxes; Time of Click shows post-delivery URL threat interception</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">5</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Export flexibility</strong> &mdash; PDF for executive and compliance delivery, CSV for SIEM ingestion or custom analysis, HTML for internal portals; up to 400,000 records per CSV export</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Reports. Open the Overview of your Sophos protection report and walk through the summary &mdash; show total protected devices, recent threat events, and policy compliance. Then open the Message Summary email report, change the date range to 90 days, and show the inbound activity breakdown by threat category. Show the scheduling workflow &mdash; click to save as a template, set a weekly cadence, and configure email delivery. Show the PDF export and highlight co-branding for MSP audiences. Finish with the At Risk Users report to show which mailboxes generate the most security events &mdash; position this as the data used to prioritise security awareness training.</p></div></div>';


// ── My Environment content ──────────────────────────────────
CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_account_health'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; System</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Account Health Check</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Continuous security posture scoring &mdash; benchmarked against peer organisations with actionable remediation guidance</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Account Health Check is a continuous security posture assessment that scores the Sophos Central configuration across multiple categories including agent mode, policies, tamper protection, endpoint exclusions, and product licence coverage. The overall score is expressed as a percentage and benchmarked against other organisations of similar size and industry, giving administrators an objective external reference point for how their configuration compares to peers. Each category shows its individual score and a detailed list of specific configuration issues that are dragging the score down, with a direct link to the setting that needs changing. Account Health Check is accessible from both the Central Overview Dashboard widget and the My Environment section, and for MDR customers it is used by the Sophos analyst team to flag configuration gaps that increase operational risk during incident response.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Account Health Check is one of the most powerful things to show during a Sophos Central demo because it immediately makes the abstract concrete. Every customer thinks their security configuration is reasonable &mdash; Account Health Check tells them objectively how it compares to their peers. When you open this screen you see a score, and below it you see exactly which configuration decisions are reducing that score. Not vague recommendations &mdash; specific, actionable items each linking directly to the setting that needs fixing. For MDR customers this screen has additional significance: our analyst team reviews Account Health Check scores as part of onboarding and flags any configuration gaps that would limit their ability to detect and respond effectively. A customer with a low Account Health Check score is effectively operating with reduced MDR visibility even if they have MDR licences. Walking a customer through their score and showing them the specific items to fix is a consultative conversation that creates immediate value before the contract is even signed.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Objective posture benchmark</strong> &mdash; the score compares configuration against peer organisations of similar size; gives a CISO an external reference point beyond internal self-assessment</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Category-level scoring</strong> &mdash; agent mode, policy coverage, tamper protection, exclusions, and licence coverage each scored separately; shows which areas carry the most risk</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Actionable remediation links</strong> &mdash; every issue in the list links directly to the specific setting that needs changing; no manual navigation required to fix flagged items</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>MDR relevance</strong> &mdash; Sophos MDR analysts use Account Health Check scores during onboarding; low scores indicate configuration gaps that reduce analyst visibility and response effectiveness</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">5</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Continuous not periodic</strong> &mdash; score updates automatically as configurations change; administrators see the impact of remediation actions reflected in the score immediately</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Account Health Check. Show the overall score and the benchmark comparison. Walk through the category breakdown and identify the lowest-scoring category. Click into that category and show the specific issues listed with their remediation links. Click one remediation link to show it navigates directly to the relevant setting. For MDR customers explain how the analyst team uses this score during onboarding. Ask the customer what their current score is &mdash; if they are live on Sophos Central &mdash; and use it as a consultative conversation starter.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_alerts'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; System</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Alerts</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Cross-product alert management &mdash; priority-ranked notifications from every Sophos product requiring administrator action</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Alerts page consolidates notifications from across all Sophos products in Sophos Central into a single prioritised list. Alerts are generated when events occur that require administrator attention &mdash; including malware detections, policy violations, device health degradation, licence expiry warnings, connectivity failures, and update failures. Each alert shows its severity level, the source product and device, the event timestamp, and a recommended action. Alerts can be acknowledged, dismissed, or actioned directly from the list. Administrators can filter by severity, product, and time range, and configure alert notification settings to receive email notifications for specific alert categories.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;The Alerts page is the triage queue for everything in your Sophos estate that needs attention right now. Every Sophos product feeds into this single list &mdash; endpoint detections, server issues, firewall connectivity problems, email configuration warnings, licence expiry notices. Without this, an administrator would need to check each product area separately to find what needs attention. With Alerts, there is one place to start the day. The severity ranking means the most critical items are always at the top. Acknowledged alerts move out of the active view so the list stays clean and actionable. For MSP administrators managing multiple tenants, the alert notification settings mean you can configure email alerts for specific categories so critical events reach you without having to log in and check manually &mdash; the console comes to you.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Cross-product alert consolidation</strong> &mdash; every Sophos product feeds into one list; eliminates the need to check each product area separately for issues requiring attention</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Severity-ranked priority</strong> &mdash; Critical and High severity alerts appear at the top; administrators triage the most important issues first without manual sorting</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Recommended actions</strong> &mdash; each alert includes a suggested response action; reduces time-to-resolution for administrators who are not product experts in every Sophos product</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Email notification configuration</strong> &mdash; specific alert categories can trigger email notifications; critical events reach the right administrator without requiring manual console checks</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Alerts. Show the current alert list and the severity distribution. Filter to Critical and High severity to show the priority triage view. Click into an alert and walk through the detail &mdash; the source product, device, event, and recommended action. Show the acknowledge workflow. Show the notification settings and explain how email alerts can be configured per category. Position Alerts as the daily starting point for administrator triage.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_device_exposure'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; System</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Device Exposure</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Windows device patch gap inventory &mdash; identify unpatched devices across the estate and prioritise remediation by exposure duration</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Device Exposure in My Environment provides an estate-wide inventory view of Windows devices that have not installed operating system updates for an extended period. Unlike the Threat Analysis Center view of Device Exposure which surfaces patch gaps in the context of active threat detections, the My Environment view focuses on the patch hygiene of the device inventory as an operational management concern. The list shows device name, operating system version, last seen date, and time since the last OS update, allowing IT administrators to identify and prioritise devices for patch remediation based on exposure duration. Devices are sortable by patch gap to surface the longest-exposed devices first. This view is particularly useful for identifying devices that were offline during normal patching cycles and have re-joined the network without receiving updates.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Device Exposure in My Environment is the patch management conversation, not the threat hunting conversation. When you are in the Threat Analysis Center and you see Device Exposure, the lens is: which of my unpatched devices also have active suspicious detections &mdash; that is a compounded risk signal. Here in My Environment the lens is different: this is your IT operations team asking which devices in the estate have the longest patch gap and need to be prioritised in the next maintenance window. These are two different audiences using the same underlying data for different purposes. For a customer who has an IT operations team separate from their security team, this view is what the IT team uses to build their patching prioritisation list without needing access to the Threat Analysis Center. It is a clean operational view of patch hygiene across the Windows estate, sorted by exposure duration so the highest-risk devices are always at the top of the list.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>IT operations lens not threat detection</strong> &mdash; this view surfaces patch hygiene as an inventory management concern; the TAC Device Exposure view adds the threat detection correlation layer</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Exposure duration sorting</strong> &mdash; devices sorted by time since last OS update; longest-exposed devices appear first for remediation prioritisation</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Offline device detection</strong> &mdash; devices that rejoined the network after an extended offline period without patching are immediately visible; a common blind spot in patch management workflows</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Separate team access</strong> &mdash; IT operations teams can use this view without needing access to the Threat Analysis Center; appropriate access separation for larger organisations</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Device Exposure under System. Sort the list by patch gap duration to show the longest-exposed devices at the top. Click a device to show its detail including OS version and last seen date. Explain the difference between this view and the TAC Device Exposure view &mdash; operational inventory management versus threat detection correlation. Show how the list can be exported for use in a patching prioritisation workflow. Ask the customer how they currently identify devices that missed patching cycles.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_computers'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Computers &amp; Servers</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Unified device inventory &mdash; all managed Windows, Mac, and Linux endpoints and servers with health status, policy compliance, and response actions</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Computers and Servers in My Environment provides a consolidated inventory view of all managed endpoints and servers across the Sophos Central estate. The list shows every managed device with its name, operating system, health state (Good, Suspicious, Bad), protection status, assigned policy, last seen date, group membership, and licence type. Administrators can filter by health state, operating system, group, and policy to identify devices requiring attention. Clicking a device opens its full detail record showing installed product version, assigned policies, recent threat events, tamper protection status, and available response actions including scan, update, isolate, and Live Response terminal access. Server devices additionally show Server Lockdown status and Linux profile assignments. The view supports bulk actions for applying policy changes or initiating scans across multiple devices simultaneously.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Computers and Servers is your device management command centre. This is where you see every managed endpoint and server in one place &mdash; not separated by product, not split across different sections of the console. The health state column is the first thing to look at. Green means good. Suspicious or Bad health means there is something on that device that needs investigation. Click any device in a Suspicious or Bad state and you go directly to its detail record showing what was detected, what policy it is on, and what your response options are. The response actions available from this single screen are significant &mdash; you can run a scan, push an update, open a Live Response terminal directly to the device, or isolate it from the network, all without any additional tools. For server-specific scenarios the Server Lockdown status column tells you immediately which servers are running in application whitelisting mode and which are not &mdash; unprotected servers in an environment where Server Lockdown is expected is a gap worth flagging.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Unified endpoint and server inventory</strong> &mdash; all managed Windows, Mac, and Linux endpoints and servers in one view; no switching between Endpoint and Server product sections</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Health state triage</strong> &mdash; Good, Suspicious, and Bad health states are visually distinct; Suspicious and Bad devices are the priority triage items requiring investigation</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Inline response actions</strong> &mdash; scan, update, isolate, and Live Response all accessible from the device detail record; complete response workflow without additional tooling</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Server Lockdown visibility</strong> &mdash; server devices show Server Lockdown status; gaps where servers should be in application whitelisting mode but are not are immediately visible</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">5</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Bulk operations</strong> &mdash; select multiple devices and apply policy changes or initiate scans simultaneously; reduces operational overhead for fleet-wide changes</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Computers and Servers. Show the full device list and filter to Bad or Suspicious health state to surface devices requiring attention. Click a device in a Bad health state and walk through the detail record &mdash; show the threat event, assigned policy, and response action options. Demonstrate initiating a scan or showing where Live Response is accessible. Switch to the server view and show the Server Lockdown status column. Show bulk action selection for a policy change. Ask the customer how many devices they currently have in a Suspicious or Bad health state in their environment.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_unmanaged'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Unmanaged Devices</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Agentless device discovery &mdash; devices detected on the network with no Sophos agent installed</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Unmanaged Devices shows devices that Sophos has detected on the network but that do not have a Sophos agent installed. These are devices that exist within the managed environment but are outside current endpoint protection coverage &mdash; including IoT devices, printers, network equipment, contractor devices, shadow IT hardware, and any managed device where the Sophos agent was removed or failed to install. The discovery mechanism uses network scanning and telemetry from managed devices to surface unmanaged neighbours. Each discovered device shows its IP address, MAC address, device type where identifiable, first seen and last seen timestamps, and the network segment it was detected on. The unmanaged device list represents the blind spot in the security estate &mdash; devices with network access but no endpoint visibility.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Unmanaged Devices is where the conversation about blind spots becomes visible. Every customer knows they have devices on their network without endpoint protection &mdash; IoT devices, printers, visitor Wi-Fi, contractor laptops, the server someone set up three years ago and forgot about. What they don&apos;t usually know is exactly how many there are and what they are. This screen shows you. Every device that Sophos has detected on the network through passive discovery that does not have a Sophos agent installed appears here. The number on this screen is often a surprise in a demo &mdash; customers expect a handful and see dozens or hundreds. The conversation this creates is: these devices have full network access, they are generating traffic, and you have zero visibility into what they are doing. They cannot be scanned, they cannot be isolated, and if one of them is compromised it has unfettered lateral movement access to your protected devices. Unmanaged Devices makes the coverage gap tangible and measurable rather than theoretical.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Network blind spot visibility</strong> &mdash; every device with network presence but no Sophos agent is surfaced here; makes the coverage gap tangible and measurable</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Device type identification</strong> &mdash; where identifiable, device type is shown including IoT, printer, network equipment, and computer; helps prioritise which unmanaged devices are highest risk</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Network segment context</strong> &mdash; shows which network segment each unmanaged device was discovered on; identifies whether unmanaged devices are on production, guest, or OT networks</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>First and last seen timestamps</strong> &mdash; tracks when each device was first discovered and most recently active; helps identify persistent unmanaged devices versus transient visitors</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Unmanaged Devices. Show the full list and the total count. Walk through a few entries &mdash; show device type, IP, MAC, and network segment. Highlight the first seen date for persistent entries that have been on the network for an extended period. Ask the customer: do you know how many unmanaged devices are on your network right now? Use the count on this screen to make the blind spot tangible. Explain what options exist for devices that should have an agent &mdash; the deploy protection workflow from this view.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_mobile'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Mobile Devices</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">iOS and Android device inventory &mdash; enrollment status, compliance posture, threat detection, and MDM policy assignment</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Devices screen is the complete inventory of all enrolled mobile devices — showing device name, platform, OS version, enrollment type, compliance status, last check-in timestamp, and available remote actions. Enrollment type indicates whether the device is corporate-owned with full MDM control or BYOD with containerised management. Remote actions include lock, full wipe, selective container wipe for BYOD, push new policy, and send message to device.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">"Every enrolled device lives here with its compliance state in real time. The enrollment type column is critical — a corporate-owned device has full MDM control, I can wipe everything. A BYOD enrolled device uses a containerised model — Sophos manages a secure corporate container for email, apps, and data, completely separate from personal photos and messages. If that employee leaves or loses their device, I trigger a selective wipe that removes only the corporate container. Their personal data is untouched. That distinction is what makes BYOD management acceptable to employees — they know IT cannot see or touch their personal content."</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Unified mobile inventory</strong> &mdash; all enrolled iOS and Android devices in one view alongside endpoint and server inventory; single console for the full managed device fleet</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Compliance status visibility</strong> &mdash; policy compliance result shown per device; non-compliant devices are immediately identifiable for remediation or access restriction</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>MTD threat detection</strong> &mdash; Intercept X for Mobile threat status shown per device; surfaces mobile-specific threats including phishing, malicious apps, and network attacks</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Remote device commands</strong> &mdash; lock, wipe, unenroll, and policy push all accessible from the device detail record; complete remote management without additional MDM console access</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Devices. Filter to non-compliant devices and click one to show the specific compliance failure reason. Show a BYOD enrolled device versus a corporate device and explain the different remote actions available. Demonstrate the remote lock action and explain how it differs from a full wipe. Show the last check-in timestamp and explain what an extended absence indicates.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_firewalls'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Firewalls</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">XGS Firewall fleet inventory &mdash; connection status, firmware version, licence state, and device management access</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Firewalls screen is the complete inventory of all Sophos Firewalls registered to the Sophos Central account — showing appliance model, serial number, firmware version, synchronisation status, last policy sync timestamp, group assignment, and available management actions. Administrators can initiate firmware updates, push configuration changes, add firewalls to groups, and access individual firewall management from this centralised list.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">"The Firewalls screen is your registered device list — every XGS appliance, virtual firewall, and Sophos Firewall Software instance under management. The firmware version column is operationally important: it shows you immediately if any firewall in the fleet is running a version behind the current release. For organisations with 10 or 50 firewalls, manually tracking firmware currency across the fleet is a real operational burden — this column does it automatically. The sync status column tells you whether each firewall has received its most recent configuration push from Central. A firewall showing out-of-sync after a policy change is a configuration consistency problem worth investigating immediately."</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Fleet connection status</strong> &mdash; shows which XGS appliances are online and which are offline; an offline firewall represents a network protection gap requiring immediate attention</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Firmware version tracking</strong> &mdash; identifies appliances running outdated firmware; critical for ensuring vulnerability patches delivered through firmware updates are applied</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Licence expiry visibility</strong> &mdash; licence expiry dates shown per appliance; prevents unexpected protection gaps from licence lapses going unnoticed</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Direct management access</strong> &mdash; click through to the firewall management interface from the inventory view; no separate login or navigation required</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Firewalls. Show the device list with model, firmware version, and sync status. Click into an individual firewall to show its management summary. Show the firmware version column and identify any firewalls on an older version. Demonstrate the group assignment and explain how a policy change to a group pushes to all member firewalls simultaneously.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_switches'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Switches</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Sophos Switch fleet inventory &mdash; connection status, port utilisation, PoE management, and firmware version tracking</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Switches screen is the complete inventory of all Sophos Switches registered to the Sophos Central account — showing each switch\'s model, firmware version, online or offline status, PoE power consumption versus budget, port utilisation, and location group assignment. This is the primary operational view for managing the entire switching estate. From here administrators can drill into individual switch detail, initiate firmware updates, assign switches to groups, and access per-port configuration without connecting to any switch\'s local interface.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">"Sophos Switches complete the unified network management story in Sophos Central. Firewall, wireless, and switching — all in the same console, all zero-touch deployable, all with the same policy-driven management model. This Switches screen is your fleet view: every switch at every site, its health, and how loaded its PoE budget is. For branch office deployments this replaces what used to require separate management platforms for each network layer. Zero-touch deployment works the same way as wireless — ship the switch to a branch, the on-site team powers it on and plugs in the uplink, the switch auto-claims to your Sophos Central account, downloads its configuration, and appears in this list within minutes. No pre-staging, no console cable, no on-site network skills needed."</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Automatic inventory</strong> &mdash; zero-touch deployed switches appear automatically in the inventory; no manual registration required for new appliances</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>PoE budget visibility</strong> &mdash; power budget and consumption shown per switch; prevents unexpected device failures in PoE-heavy environments approaching capacity</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Port-level detail</strong> &mdash; click through to see per-port status, connected device information, and PoE allocation; complete switch visibility without separate management tooling</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Firmware tracking</strong> &mdash; firmware version shown per switch; identifies appliances behind on updates across the switch fleet</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Switches. Show the fleet inventory and point out the health status and PoE consumption columns. Click into an individual switch to show the port-level detail view. Show the firmware version column and identify any switches on older firmware. Walk through the zero-touch claim process using the Add Switch workflow. Ask the customer how they currently manage their switch configuration across multiple sites.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_ztna_gateways'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">ZTNA Gateways</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Zero Trust Network Access gateway fleet &mdash; deployment status, connected users, resource access logs, and health monitoring</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Gateways screen shows all deployed ZTNA gateways — their mode (Sophos Cloud managed or on-premises VMware and Hyper-V), current health status, Points of Presence configuration, connected resource count, and high availability status. Gateways are the enforcement points through which all ZTNA-protected resource access is brokered. Sophos Cloud gateways are infrastructure managed by Sophos with automatic PoP failover. On-premises gateways are deployed behind the customer firewall for lower latency access to internal applications.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">"The Gateway is what replaces your VPN concentrator — and the difference in model is fundamental. A VPN concentrator gives authenticated users access to your network. A ZTNA gateway gives authenticated users access to specific applications only — the network behind the gateway is never exposed. For Sophos Cloud gateways, there is nothing for you to manage. Sophos runs the infrastructure, handles PoP failover, and patches the platform. If a PoP in one region degrades, traffic automatically routes through the nearest available PoP — zero outage, no intervention. For on-premises gateways deployed in a data centre or behind a firewall, management is entirely through Sophos Central. The gateway VM sits inside your perimeter and only the applications you explicitly publish are reachable through it."</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Multi-gateway fleet visibility</strong> &mdash; all ZTNA gateway instances in one view; confirms health and availability across on-premises and cloud gateway deployments</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Active session monitoring</strong> &mdash; connected user count and session information per gateway; identifies capacity constraints before they impact user experience</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Resource and user assignment</strong> &mdash; gateway detail shows which resources and users are assigned; validates that access control assignments are correctly configured</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Cloud and on-premises support</strong> &mdash; gateways deployed in AWS, Azure, GCP, or on-premises all appear in the same inventory view</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Gateways. Show both Sophos Cloud and on-premises gateway types if available. Click into a Sophos Cloud gateway and show the PoP selection and secondary PoP configuration for HA. Show the health status and connected resource count. Explain how Sophos Cloud gateway HA works automatically compared to the manual HA configuration required with traditional VPN concentrators.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_wireless_aps'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; Devices</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Wireless Access Points</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Sophos AP fleet inventory &mdash; connection status, client count, channel utilisation, and firmware management</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">The Access Points screen is the complete inventory of all deployed Sophos APs — showing model, firmware version, location group, IP address, connected client count, channel utilization, and health status. Firmware management is centralised — push updates to all APs simultaneously or stagger by location group. APs can be organised into groups by site, floor, or building with separate configuration profiles per group, allowing different SSID sets, transmit power, and channel settings per location.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">"Zero-touch deployment is the operational story here. A new AP ships directly to a branch office — the on-site team mounts it, plugs in a PoE Ethernet cable, and powers it on. The AP scans for internet access, finds it, calls home to your Sophos Central tenant, auto-claims to your account, and downloads its configuration profile. The SSID names, passwords, VLAN assignments, and all wireless settings are applied automatically. No technician expertise needed at the branch, no pre-staging, no configuration files to transfer. Firmware management works the same way — push a firmware update from Central and every AP in the fleet updates on schedule without anyone touching a device."</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Fleet health at a glance</strong> &mdash; connection status and client count for every AP in the estate; offline APs represent wireless coverage gaps requiring immediate attention</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Client load distribution</strong> &mdash; client count per AP identifies load imbalances; high client count on individual APs indicates where additional capacity may be needed</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Zero-touch inventory</strong> &mdash; APs deployed with zero-touch provisioning appear automatically; no manual registration or AP-by-AP management required</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Channel and frequency visibility</strong> &mdash; channel and band assignment shown per AP; supports troubleshooting interference and coverage issues without separate wireless management tools</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to Access Points. Show the AP inventory with model and firmware version. Click an AP and show its location group, connected clients, and channel utilization. Show the firmware update workflow — select a group of APs and schedule an update. Walk through the zero-touch deployment process using the AP claim and configuration steps.</p></div></div>';

CENTRAL_CONTENT['env_users_groups'] = '<div style="padding:28px 0"><div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--sophos-accent);font-weight:600;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:6px">My Environment &rsaquo; People</div><h1 style="font-size:26px;font-weight:700;color:var(--sophos-dark);margin:0 0 4px">Users &amp; Groups</h1><p style="font-size:13px;color:#666;margin:0 0 20px">Directory-synchronised user and group inventory &mdash; protection status, device assignments, policy group membership, and access management</p><div style="border-top:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:20px"></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:8px">&#9432; WHAT THIS SCREEN SHOWS</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Users and Groups in My Environment provides the people-centric view of the Sophos Central estate. The Users section lists all users synchronised from Active Directory, Azure AD, or Google Workspace, showing each user&apos;s name, email address, assigned devices, protection status, policy group membership, and last active timestamp. Users can be searched, filtered by group, and individually managed. The Groups section shows policy groups used to assign Sophos protection policies to collections of users &mdash; allowing policy assignments to be managed at the group level and inherited by members rather than configured device by device. User records link to their assigned devices, making Users and Groups the starting point for people-centric investigation workflows when an incident involves a specific user account.</p></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#127908; TALK TRACK</div><div style="background:var(--sophos-dark);border-left:4px solid var(--sophos-accent);border-radius:0 8px 8px 0;padding:16px 20px"><p style="font-size:13px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);line-height:1.8;margin:0;font-style:italic">&quot;Users and Groups is where Sophos Central shifts from a device-centric view to a people-centric view. For most security investigations and policy management workflows, you eventually need to answer the question: who is on this device, and what other devices does that user have access to? Users and Groups is where those answers live. Every user synchronised from your Active Directory or Azure AD appears here with their assigned devices, their policy group membership, and their protection status. When an incident involves a compromised user account &mdash; which is the starting point for a significant proportion of breaches &mdash; this is where you see the full picture of that user&apos;s footprint: every device they are assigned to, every policy group they belong to, every licence they are consuming. Policy Groups make fleet-wide policy management scalable &mdash; instead of assigning policies device by device, you manage group membership and policies flow down automatically. Add a new device for a user in the finance group and it inherits the finance policy set immediately without manual configuration.&quot;</p></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:16px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sophos-blue);margin-bottom:12px">&#128203; KEY POINTS TO MAKE</div><div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px"><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">1</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Directory synchronisation</strong> &mdash; users sync automatically from Active Directory, Azure AD, or Google Workspace; user records are always current without manual management</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">2</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>People-centric investigation</strong> &mdash; click a user to see all their assigned devices, policy groups, and protection status; essential starting point when an incident involves a specific user account</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">3</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Policy group management</strong> &mdash; groups control policy assignment at scale; add a device to a group and it inherits the correct policy set automatically without per-device configuration</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">4</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Protection status per user</strong> &mdash; shows which users have licensed Sophos protection across their devices and which have coverage gaps</p></div><div style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start"><div style="background:var(--sophos-blue);color:#fff;border-radius:50%;width:22px;height:22px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:1px">5</div><p style="margin:0;font-size:13px;color:#333;line-height:1.6"><strong>Cross-product user linking</strong> &mdash; user records connect to endpoint protection, email security, mobile management, and ZTNA access; complete cross-product user footprint in one view</p></div></div></div><div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:10px;padding:20px 24px"><div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#e67e00;margin-bottom:8px">&#9654; DEMO ACTION</div><p style="font-size:13px;color:#444;line-height:1.7;margin:0">Navigate to My Environment then Users and Groups. Show the user list with device count and protection status. Search for a specific user and click through to their record &mdash; show assigned devices, policy group membership, and licence consumption. Show the Groups section and explain how policy assignment works at the group level. Create a brief scenario: a user account has been flagged in an incident &mdash; show how Users and Groups gives you their full device footprint in seconds. Ask the customer how they currently manage policy assignments when onboarding new users or devices.</p></div></div>';


